# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:webview-native/blink-browser-engine] To create Chrome, Google initially chose to use Apple's WebKit engine.
[src:webview-native/blink-browser-engine] However, Google needed to make substantial changes to its code to support Chrome's novel multi-process browser architecture.
[src:webview-native/blink-browser-engine] Over the course of several years, the divergence from Apple's version increased, so Google decided to officially fork its version as Blink in 2013.
[src:webview-native/blink-browser-engine] Blink's name was influenced by two factors: the implication of speed, and a reference to the non-standard blink HTML element, popularised by Netscape Navigator, but which was never actually implemented within Blink.
[src:webview-native/blink-browser-engine] By commit count, Google was the largest contributor to the WebKit project from late 2009 until the fork in 2013.
[src:webview-native/blink-browser-engine] One of the first changes of the new fork was to deprecate CSS vendor prefixes, including WebKit's; experimental Blink functionality is instead enabled on an opt-in basis.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] CSS is designed to enable the separation of content and presentation, including layout, colors, and fonts.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] Separation of formatting and content also makes it feasible to present the same markup page in different styles for different rendering methods, such as on-screen, in print, by voice (via speech-based browser or screen reader), and on Braille-based tactile devices.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] CSS also has rules for alternative formatting if the content is accessed on a mobile device.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] The name *cascading* comes from the specified priority scheme to determine which declaration applies if more than one declaration of a property match a particular element.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] This cascading priority scheme is predictable.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] The CSS specifications are maintained by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] Internet media type (MIME type) `text/css` is registered for use with CSS by RFC 2318 (March 1998).
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] The W3C operates a free CSS validation service for CSS documents.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] In addition to HTML, other markup languages support the use of CSS including XHTML, plain XML, SVG, and XUL.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] CSS is also used in the GTK widget toolkit.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] CSS has a simple syntax and uses a number of English keywords to specify the names of various style properties.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] A style sheet consists of a list of *rules*.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] Each rule or rule-set consists of one or more *selectors*, and a *declaration block*.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] In CSS, *selectors* declare which part of the markup a style applies to by matching tags and attributes in the markup itself.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] Classes and IDs are case-sensitive, start with letters, and can include alphanumeric characters, hyphens, and underscores.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] A class may apply to any number of instances of any element.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] An ID may only be applied to a single element.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] One example of a widely used pseudo-class is `:hover`, which identifies content only when the user "points to" the visible element, usually by holding the mouse cursor over it.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] It is appended to a selector as in `a:hover` or `#elementid:hover`.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] A pseudo-class classifies document elements, such as `:link` or `:visited`, whereas a *pseudo-element* makes a selection that may consist of partial elements, such as `::first-line` or `::first-letter`.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] Note the distinction between the double-colon notation used for pseudo-elements and the single-colon notation used for pseudo-classes.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] Multiple simple selectors may be joined using combinators to specify elements by location, element type, id, class, or any combination thereof.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] The order of the selectors is important.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] For example, `div .myClass {color: red;}` applies to all elements of class myClass that are inside div elements, whereas `.myClass div {color: red;}` applies to all div elements that are inside elements of class myClass.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] This is not to be confused with concatenated identifiers such as `div.myClass {color: red;}` which applies to div elements of class myClass.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] The following table provides a summary of selector syntax indicating usage and the version of CSS that introduced it.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] A declaration block consists of a pair of braces (`{}`) enclosing a semicolon-separated list of *declarations*.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] Each declaration itself consists of a *property*, a colon (`:`), and a *value*.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] Optional white-space may be around the declaration block, declarations, colons, and semi-colons for readability.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] Properties are specified in the CSS standard.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] Each property has a set of possible values.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] Some properties can affect any type of element, and others apply only to particular groups of elements.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] Values may be keywords, such as "center" or "inherit", or numerical values, such as `200px` (200 pixels), `50vw` (50 percent of the viewport width) or 80% (80 percent of the parent element's width).
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] Color values can be specified with keywords (e.g.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] `rgb(255, 0, 0)`), RGBA values that specify both color and alpha transparency (e.g.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] Non-zero numeric values representing linear measures must include a length unit, which is either an alphabetic code or abbreviation, as in `200px` or `50vw`; or a percentage sign, as in `80%`.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] These eight units were a feature of CSS 1 and retained in all subsequent revisions.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] The proposed CSS Values and Units Module Level 3 will, if adopted as a W3C Recommendation, provide seven further length units: `ch`; `Q`; `rem`; `vh`; `vmax`; `vmin`; and `vw`.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] Before CSS, nearly all presentational attributes of HTML documents were contained within the HTML markup.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] That is, all font colors, background styles, element alignments, borders, and sizes had to be explicitly described (often repeatedly) within the HTML.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] CSS lets authors move much of that information to another file, the style sheet, resulting in considerably simpler HTML.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] And additionally, as more and more devices are able to access responsive web pages, different screen sizes and layouts begin to appear.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] Customizing a website for each device size is costly and increasingly difficult.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] The modular nature of CSS means that styles can be reused in different parts of a site or even across sites, promoting consistency and efficiency.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] For example, headings (`h1` elements), sub-headings (`h2`), sub-sub-headings (`h3`), etc., are defined structurally using HTML.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] In print and on the screen, choice of font, size, color and emphasis for these elements is *presentational*.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] Before CSS, document authors who wanted to assign such typographic characteristics to, say, all `h2` headings had to repeat HTML presentational markup for each occurrence of that heading type.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] This made documents more complex, larger, and more error-prone and difficult to maintain.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] CSS allows the separation of presentation from structure.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] CSS can define color, font, text alignment, size, borders, spacing, layout and many other typographic characteristics, and can do so independently for on-screen and printed views.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] CSS also defines non-visual styles, such as reading speed and emphasis for aural text readers.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] The W3C has now deprecated the use of all presentational HTML markup.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] The advantages of this may not be immediately clear but the power of CSS becomes more apparent when the style properties are placed in an internal style element or, even better, an external CSS file.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] All `h1` elements in the document will then automatically become red without requiring any explicit code.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] rather than by laboriously going through the document and changing the color for each individual `h1` element.
[src:webview-native/cascading-style-sheets] This further decouples the styling from the HTML document and makes it possible to restyle multiple documents by simply editing a shared external CSS file.
[src:webview-native/html] Web browsers receive HTML documents from a web server or from local storage and render the documents into multimedia web pages.
[src:webview-native/html] HTML describes the structure of a web page semantically and originally included cues for its appearance.
[src:webview-native/html] HTML elements are the building blocks of HTML pages.
[src:webview-native/html] With HTML constructs, images and other objects such as interactive forms may be embedded into the rendered page.
[src:webview-native/html] HTML provides a means to create structured documents by denoting structural semantics for text such as headings, paragraphs, lists, links, quotes, and other items.
[src:webview-native/html] HTML elements are delineated by *tags*, written using angle brackets.
[src:webview-native/html] Tags such as `<img>` and `<input>` directly introduce content into the page.
[src:webview-native/html] Other tags such as `<p>` and its corresponding closing tag `</p>` surround and provide information about document text and may include sub-element tags.
[src:webview-native/html] Browsers do not display the HTML tags, but use them to interpret the content of the page.
[src:webview-native/html] HTML can embed programs written in a scripting language such as JavaScript, which affects the behavior and content of web pages.
[src:webview-native/html] The inclusion of CSS defines the look and layout of content.
[src:webview-native/html] The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), former maintainer of the HTML and current maintainer of the CSS standards, has encouraged the use of CSS over explicit presentational HTML since 1997.
[src:webview-native/html] A form of HTML, known as HTML5, is used to display video and audio, primarily using the `<canvas>` element, together with JavaScript.
[src:webview-native/html] In 1980, the physicist Tim Berners-Lee, a contractor at CERN, proposed and prototyped ENQUIRE, a system for CERN researchers to use and share documents.
[src:webview-native/html] In 1989, Berners-Lee wrote a memo proposing an Internet-based hypertext system.
[src:webview-native/html] Berners-Lee specified HTML and wrote the browser and server software in late 1990.
[src:webview-native/html] That year, Berners-Lee and CERN data systems engineer Robert Cailliau collaborated on a joint request for funding, but the project was not formally adopted by CERN.
[src:webview-native/html] In his personal notes of 1990, Berners-Lee listed "some of the many areas in which hypertext is used"; an encyclopedia is the first entry.
[src:webview-native/html] The first publicly available description of HTML was a document called "HTML Tags", first mentioned on the Internet by Tim Berners-Lee in late 1991.
[src:webview-native/html] It describes 18 elements comprising the initial, relatively simple design of HTML.
[src:webview-native/html] Except for the hyperlink tag, these were strongly influenced by CERN SGML, an in-house Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML)-based documentation format at CERN.
[src:webview-native/html] Eleven of these elements still exist in HTML 4.
[src:webview-native/html] HTML is a markup language that web browsers use to interpret and compose text, images, and other material into visible or audible web pages.
[src:webview-native/html] Default characteristics for every item of HTML markup are defined in the browser, and these characteristics can be altered or enhanced by the web page designer's additional use of CSS.
[src:webview-native/html] These formatting commands were derived from the commands used by typesetters to manually format documents.
[src:webview-native/html] However, the SGML concept of generalized markup is based on elements (nested annotated ranges with attributes) rather than merely print effects, with separate structure and markup.
[src:webview-native/html] HTML has been progressively moved in this direction with CSS.
[src:webview-native/html] Berners-Lee considered HTML to be an application of SGML.
[src:webview-native/html] The draft expired after six months, but was notable for its acknowledgment of the NCSA Mosaic browser's custom tag for embedding in-line images, reflecting the IETF's philosophy of basing standards on successful prototypes.
[src:webview-native/html] Similarly, Dave Raggett's competing Internet Draft, "HTML+ (Hypertext Markup Format)", from late 1993, suggested standardizing already-implemented features like tables and fill-out forms.
[src:webview-native/html] After the HTML and HTML+ drafts expired in early 1994, the IETF created an HTML Working Group.
[src:webview-native/html] In 1995, this working group completed "HTML 2.0", the first HTML specification intended to be treated as a standard against which future implementations should be based.
[src:webview-native/html] Further development under the auspices of the IETF was stalled by competing interests.
[src:webview-native/html] Since 1996, the HTML specifications have been maintained, with input from commercial software vendors, by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:webview-native/html] In 2000, HTML became an international standard (ISO/IEC 15445:2000).
[src:webview-native/html] HTML 4.01 was published in late 1999, with further errata published through 2001.
[src:webview-native/html] In 2004, development began on HTML5 in the Web Hypertext Application Technology Working Group (WHATWG), which became a joint deliverable with the W3C in 2008, and was completed and standardized on 28 October 2014.
[src:webview-native/html] It was the first version developed and standardized exclusively by the W3C, as the IETF had closed its HTML Working Group on 12 September 1996.
[src:webview-native/html] were omitted due to a mutual agreement between the two companies.
[src:webview-native/html] HTML 4 is an SGML application conforming to ISO 8879 – SGML.
[src:webview-native/html] was reissued with minor edits without incrementing the version number.
[src:webview-native/html] HTML", based on HTML 4.01 Strict) was published as an ISO/IEC international standard.
[src:webview-native/html] (ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1, Subcommittee 34 – Document description and processing languages).
[src:webview-native/html] After HTML 4.01, there were no new versions of HTML for many years, as the development of the parallel, XML-based language XHTML occupied the W3C's HTML Working Group.
[src:webview-native/html] an informal CERN document listing 18 HTML tags, was first mentioned in public.
[src:webview-native/html] IIIR Working Group as an Internet Draft (a rough proposal for a standard).
[src:webview-native/html] HTML+ was published by the IETF as an Internet Draft and was a competing proposal to the Hypertext Markup Language draft.
[src:webview-native/html] It included many of the capabilities that were in Raggett's HTML+ proposal, such as support for tables, text flow around figures, and the display of complex mathematical formulas.
[src:webview-native/html] but HTML 3.0 did not succeed for several reasons.
[src:webview-native/html] The draft was considered very large at 150 pages and the pace of browser development, as well as the number of interested parties, had outstripped the resources of the IETF.
[src:webview-native/html] Browser vendors, including Microsoft and Netscape at the time, chose to implement different subsets of HTML 3's draft features as well as to introduce their own extensions to it.
[src:webview-native/html] has abandoned any attempt to be an SGML application and has explicitly defined its own "html" serialization, in addition to an alternative XML-based XHTML5 serialization.
[src:webview-native/html] On 14 February 2011, the W3C extended the charter of its HTML Working Group with clear milestones for HTML5.
[src:webview-native/html] In May 2011, the working group advanced HTML5 to "Last Call", an invitation to communities inside and outside W3C to confirm the technical soundness of the specification.
[src:webview-native/html] The W3C developed a comprehensive test suite to achieve broad interoperability for the full specification by 2014, which was the target date for recommendation.
[src:webview-native/html] In January 2011, the WHATWG renamed its "HTML5" living standard to "HTML".
[src:webview-native/html] The W3C nevertheless continued its project to release HTML5.
[src:webview-native/html] W3C will continue the HTML5 specification work, focusing on a single definitive standard, which is considered a "snapshot" by WHATWG.
[src:webview-native/html] The WHATWG organization will continue its work with HTML5 as a "Living Standard".
[src:webview-native/html] The concept of a living standard is that it is never complete and is always being updated and improved.
[src:webview-native/html] New features can be added but functionality will not be removed.
[src:webview-native/html] In December 2012, W3C designated HTML5 as a Candidate Recommendation.
[src:webview-native/html] is "two 100% complete and fully interoperable implementations".
[src:webview-native/html] In September 2014, W3C moved HTML5 to Proposed Recommendation.
[src:webview-native/html] meaning the specification process is complete.
[src:webview-native/html] XHTML is a separate language that began as a reformulation of HTML 4.01 using XML 1.0.
[src:webview-native/html] It is now referred to as *the XML syntax for HTML* and is no longer being developed as a separate standard.
[src:webview-native/html] On 28 May 2019, the W3C announced that WHATWG would be the sole publisher of the HTML and DOM standards.
[src:webview-native/html] The W3C and WHATWG had been publishing competing standards since 2012.
[src:webview-native/html] While the W3C standard was identical to the WHATWG in 2007 the standards have since progressively diverged due to different design decisions.
[src:webview-native/html] The WHATWG "Living Standard" had been the *de facto* web standard for some time.
[src:webview-native/html] The W3C periodically reviews and publishes snapshots of the WHATWG HTML specification as W3C Recommendations.
[src:webview-native/html] HTML markup consists of several key components, including those called *tags* (and their *attributes*), character-based *data types*, *character references* and *entity references*.
[src:webview-native/html] HTML tags most commonly come in pairs like `<h1>` and `</h1>`, although some represent *empty elements* and so are unpaired, for example `<img>`.
[src:webview-native/html] The first tag in such a pair is the *start tag*, and the second is the *end tag* (they are also called *opening tags* and *closing tags*).
[src:webview-native/html] Another important component is the HTML *document type declaration*, which triggers standards mode rendering.
[src:webview-native/html] The text between `<html>` and `</html>` describes the web page, and the text between `<body>` and `</body>` is the visible page content.
[src:webview-native/html] The markup text `<title>This is a title</title>` defines the browser page title shown on browser tabs and window titles and the tag `<div>` defines a division of the page used for easy styling.
[src:webview-native/html] Between `<head>` and `</head>`, a `<meta>` element can be used to define webpage metadata.
[src:webview-native/html] The Document Type Declaration `<!DOCTYPE html>` is for HTML5.
[src:webview-native/html] If a declaration is not included, various browsers will revert to "quirks mode" for rendering.
[src:webview-native/html] HTML documents imply a structure of nested HTML elements.
[src:webview-native/html] These are indicated in the document by HTML *tags*, enclosed in angle brackets.
[src:webview-native/html] In the simple, general case, the extent of an element is indicated by a pair of tags: a "start tag" `<p>` and "end tag" `</p>`.
[src:webview-native/html] The text content of the element, if any, is placed between these tags.
[src:webview-native/html] Tags may also enclose further tag markup between the start and end, including a mixture of tags and text.
[src:webview-native/html] This indicates further (nested) elements, as children of the parent element.
[src:webview-native/html] The start tag may also include the element's *attributes* within the tag.
[src:webview-native/html] Some elements, such as the line break `<br>` do not permit *any* embedded content, either text or further tags.
[src:webview-native/html] These require only a single empty tag (akin to a start tag) and do not use an end tag.
[src:webview-native/html] Many tags, particularly the closing end tag for the very commonly used paragraph element `<p>`, are optional.
[src:webview-native/html] An HTML browser or other agent can infer the closure for the end of an element from the context and the structural rules defined by the HTML standard.
[src:webview-native/html] These rules are complex and not widely understood by most HTML authors.
[src:webview-native/html] The general form of an HTML element is therefore: `<tag attribute1="value1" attribute2="value2">''content''</tag>`.
[src:webview-native/html] Some HTML elements are defined as *empty elements* and take the form `<tag attribute1="value1" attribute2="value2">`.
[src:webview-native/html] Empty elements may enclose no content, for instance, the `<br>` tag or the inline `<img>` tag.
[src:webview-native/html] The name of an HTML element is the name used in the tags.
[src:webview-native/html] The end tag's name is preceded by a slash character `/`.
[src:webview-native/html] If a tag has no content, an end tag is not allowed.
[src:webview-native/html] If attributes are not mentioned, default values are used in each case.
[src:webview-native/html] Header of the HTML document: `<head>...</head>`.
[src:webview-native/html] CSS can substantially change the rendering.
[src:webview-native/html] The difference between `<br>` and `<p>` is that `<br>` breaks a line without altering the semantic structure of the page, whereas `<p>` sections the page into paragraphs.
[src:webview-native/html] The element `<br>` is an *empty element* in that, although it may have attributes, it can take no content and it must not have an end tag.
[src:webview-native/html] The `href` attribute holds the URL address of the link.
[src:webview-native/html] Comments can help in the understanding of the markup and do not display in the webpage.
[src:webview-native/html] Most of the attributes of an element are name–value pairs, separated by `=` and written within the start tag of an element after the element's name.
[src:webview-native/html] The value may be enclosed in single or double quotes, although values consisting of certain characters can be left unquoted in HTML (but not XHTML).
[src:webview-native/html] Leaving attribute values unquoted is considered unsafe.
[src:webview-native/html] In contrast with name-value pair attributes, there are some attributes that affect the element simply by their presence in the start tag of the element, like the `ismap` attribute for the `img` element.
[src:webview-native/html] Most elements take the language-related attribute `dir` to specify text direction, such as with "rtl" for right-to-left text in, for example, Arabic, Persian or Hebrew.
[src:webview-native/html] As of version 4.0, HTML defines a set of 252 character entity references and a set of 1,114,050 numeric character references, both of which allow individual characters to be written via simple markup, rather than literally.
[src:webview-native/html] A literal character and its markup counterpart are considered equivalent and are rendered identically.
[src:webview-native/html] The ability to "escape" characters in this way allows for the characters `<` and `&` (when written as `&lt;` and `&amp;`, respectively) to be interpreted as character data, rather than markup.
[src:webview-native/html] For example, a literal `<` normally indicates the start of a tag, and `&` normally indicates the start of a character entity reference or numeric character reference; writing it as `&amp;` or `&#x26;` or `&#38;` allows `&` to be included in the content of an element or in the value of an attribute.
[src:webview-native/html] The double-quote character (`"`), when not used to quote an attribute value, must also be escaped as `&quot;` or `&#x22;` or `&#34;` when it appears within the attribute value itself.
[src:webview-native/html] Equivalently, the single-quote character (`'`), when not used to quote an attribute value, must also be escaped as `&#x27;` or `&#39;` (or as `&apos;` in HTML5 or XHTML documents) when it appears within the attribute value itself.
[src:webview-native/html] If document authors overlook the need to escape such characters, some browsers can be very forgiving and try to use context to guess their intent.
[src:webview-native/html] The result is still invalid markup, which makes the document less accessible to other browsers and to other user agents that may try to parse the document for search and indexing purposes for example.
[src:webview-native/html] Escaping also allows for characters that are not easily typed, or that are not available in the document's character encoding, to be represented within the element and attribute content.
[src:webview-native/html] Unicode character encodings such as UTF-8 are compatible with all modern browsers and allow direct access to almost all the characters of the world's writing systems.
[src:webview-native/html] HTML defines several data types for element content, such as script data and stylesheet data, and a plethora of types for attribute values, including IDs, names, URIs, numbers, units of length, languages, media descriptors, colors, character encodings, dates and times, and so on.
[src:webview-native/html] All of these data types are specializations of character data.
[src:webview-native/html] HTML documents are required to start with a document type declaration (informally, a "doctype").
[src:webview-native/html] In browsers, the doctype helps to define the rendering mode—particularly whether to use quirks mode.
[src:webview-native/html] The original purpose of the doctype was to enable the parsing and validation of HTML documents by SGML tools based on the document type definition (DTD).
[src:webview-native/html] The DTD to which the DOCTYPE refers contains a machine-readable grammar specifying the permitted and prohibited content for a document conforming to such a DTD.
[src:webview-native/html] Browsers, on the other hand, do not implement HTML as an application of SGML and as consequence do not read the DTD.
[src:webview-native/html] This declaration references the DTD for the "strict" version of HTML 4.01.
[src:webview-native/html] SGML-based validators read the DTD in order to properly parse the document and to perform validation.
[src:webview-native/html] In modern browsers, a valid doctype activates standards mode as opposed to quirks mode.
[src:webview-native/html] In addition, HTML 4.01 provides Transitional and Frameset DTDs, as explained below.
[src:webview-native/html] The transitional type is the most inclusive, incorporating current tags as well as older or "deprecated" tags, with the Strict DTD excluding deprecated tags.
[src:webview-native/html] The frameset has all tags necessary to make frames on a page along with the tags included in transitional type.
[src:webview-native/html] Semantic HTML is a way of writing HTML that emphasizes the meaning of the encoded information over its presentation (look).
[src:webview-native/html] HTML has included semantic markup from its inception, but has also included presentational markup, such as `<font>`, `<i>`, and `<center>` tags.
[src:webview-native/html] There are also the semantically neutral div and span tags.
[src:webview-native/html] Since the late 1990s, when Cascading Style Sheets were beginning to work in most browsers, web authors have been encouraged to avoid the use of presentational HTML markup with a view to the separation of content and presentation.
[src:webview-native/html] In a 2001 discussion of the Semantic Web, Tim Berners-Lee and others gave examples of ways in which intelligent software "agents" may one day automatically crawl the web and find, filter, and correlate previously unrelated, published facts for the benefit of human users.
[src:webview-native/html] Such agents are not commonplace even now, but some of the ideas of Web 2.0, mashups and price comparison websites may be coming close.
[src:webview-native/html] An important type of web agent that does crawl and read web pages automatically, without prior knowledge of what it might find, is the web crawler or search-engine spider.
[src:webview-native/html] These software agents are dependent on the semantic clarity of web pages they find as they use various techniques and algorithms to read and index millions of web pages a day and provide web users with search facilities without which the World Wide Web's usefulness would be greatly reduced.
[src:webview-native/html] Presentational markup tags are deprecated in current HTML and XHTML recommendations.
[src:webview-native/html] The majority of presentational features from previous versions of HTML are no longer allowed as they lead to poorer accessibility, higher cost of site maintenance, and larger document sizes.
[src:webview-native/html] Good semantic HTML also improves the accessibility of web documents (see also Web Content Accessibility Guidelines).
[src:webview-native/html] For example, when a screen reader or audio browser can correctly ascertain the structure of a document, it will not waste the visually impaired user's time by reading out repeated or irrelevant information when it has been marked up correctly.
[src:webview-native/html] HTML documents can be delivered by the same means as any other computer file.
[src:webview-native/html] However, they are most often delivered either by HTTP from a web server or by email.
[src:webview-native/html] The World Wide Web is composed primarily of HTML documents transmitted from web servers to web browsers using the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:webview-native/html] However, HTTP is used to serve images, sound, and other content, in addition to HTML.
[src:webview-native/html] To allow the web browser to know how to handle each document it receives, other information is transmitted along with the document.
[src:webview-native/html] This meta data usually includes the MIME type (e.g., text/html or application/xhtml+xml) and the character encoding (see Character encodings in HTML).
[src:webview-native/html] In modern browsers, the MIME type that is sent with the HTML document may affect how the document is initially interpreted.
[src:webview-native/html] A document sent with the XHTML MIME type is expected to be well-formed XML; syntax errors may cause the browser to fail to render it.
[src:webview-native/html] The same document sent with the HTML MIME type might be displayed successfully since some browsers are more lenient with HTML.
[src:webview-native/html] The W3C recommendations state that XHTML 1.0 documents that follow guidelines set forth in the recommendation's Appendix C may be labeled with either MIME Type.
[src:webview-native/html] XHTML 1.1 also states that XHTML 1.1 documents should be labeled with either MIME type.
[src:webview-native/html] Most graphical email clients allow the use of a subset of HTML (often ill-defined) to provide formatting and semantic markup not available with plain text.
[src:webview-native/html] This may include typographic information like colored headings, emphasized and quoted text, inline images and diagrams.
[src:webview-native/html] Many such clients include both a GUI editor for composing HTML e-mail messages and a rendering engine for displaying them.
[src:webview-native/html] Use of HTML in e-mail is criticized by some because of compatibility issues, because it can help disguise phishing attacks, because of accessibility issues for blind or visually impaired people, because it can confuse spam filters and because the message size is larger than plain text.
[src:webview-native/html] The most common filename extension for files containing HTML is .html.
[src:webview-native/html] A common abbreviation of this is .htm, which originated because some operating systems limit file extensions to three letters.
[src:webview-native/html] An HTML Application (HTA; file extension .hta) is a Microsoft Windows application that uses HTML and Dynamic HTML in a browser to provide the application's graphical interface.
[src:webview-native/html] A regular HTML file is confined to the security model of the web browser's security, communicating only to web servers and manipulating only web page objects and site cookies.
[src:webview-native/html] An HTA runs as a fully trusted application and therefore has more privileges, like creation/editing/removal of files and Windows Registry entries.
[src:webview-native/html] Because they operate outside the browser's security model, HTAs cannot be executed via HTTP, but must be downloaded (just like an EXE file) and executed from local file system.
[src:webview-native/html] Since its inception, HTML and its associated protocols gained acceptance relatively quickly.
[src:webview-native/html] However, no clear standards existed in the early years of the language.
[src:webview-native/html] Though its creators originally conceived of HTML as a semantic language devoid of presentation details, practical uses pushed many presentational elements and attributes into the language, driven largely by the various browser vendors.
[src:webview-native/html] The latest standards surrounding HTML reflect efforts to overcome the sometimes chaotic development of the language and to create a rational foundation for building both meaningful and well-presented documents.
[src:webview-native/html] To return HTML to its role as a semantic language, the W3C has developed style languages such as CSS and XSL to shoulder the burden of presentation.
[src:webview-native/html] In conjunction, the HTML specification has slowly reined in the presentational elements.
[src:webview-native/html] There are two axes differentiating various variations of HTML as currently specified: SGML-based HTML versus XML-based HTML (referred to as XHTML) on one axis, and strict versus transitional (loose) versus frameset on the other axis.
[src:webview-native/html] One difference in the latest HTML specifications lies in the distinction between the SGML-based specification and the XML-based specification.
[src:webview-native/html] The XML-based specification is usually called XHTML to distinguish it clearly from the more traditional definition.
[src:webview-native/html] However, the root element name continues to be "html" even in the XHTML-specified HTML.
[src:webview-native/html] The W3C intended XHTML 1.0 to be identical to HTML 4.01 except where limitations of XML over the more complex SGML require workarounds.
[src:webview-native/html] Because XHTML and HTML are closely related, they are sometimes documented in parallel.
[src:webview-native/html] In such circumstances, some authors conflate the two names as (X)HTML or X(HTML).
[src:webview-native/html] Like HTML 4.01, XHTML 1.0 has three sub-specifications: strict, transitional, and frameset.
[src:webview-native/html] Aside from the different opening declarations for a document, the differences between an HTML 4.01 and XHTML 1.0 document—in each of the corresponding DTDs—are largely syntactic.
[src:webview-native/html] The underlying syntax of HTML allows many shortcuts that XHTML does not, such as elements with optional opening or closing tags, and even empty elements which must not have an end tag.
[src:webview-native/html] By contrast, XHTML requires all elements to have an opening tag and a closing tag.
[src:webview-native/html] XHTML, however, also introduces a new shortcut: an XHTML tag may be opened and closed within the same tag, by including a slash before the end of the tag like this: `<br/>`.
[src:webview-native/html] The introduction of this shorthand, which is not used in the SGML declaration for HTML 4.01, may confuse earlier software unfamiliar with this new convention.
[src:webview-native/html] A fix for this is remove the slash preceding the closing angle bracket, as such: `<br>`.
[src:webview-native/html] To understand the subtle differences between HTML and XHTML, consider the transformation of a valid and well-formed XHTML 1.0 document that adheres to Appendix C (see below) into a valid HTML 4.01 document.
[src:webview-native/html] Change the document type declaration from XHTML 1.0 to HTML 4.01.
[src:webview-native/html] Ensure that the document's MIME type is set to `text/html`.
[src:webview-native/html] For both HTML and XHTML, this comes from the HTTP `Content-Type` header sent by the server.
[src:webview-native/html] Change the XML empty-element syntax to an HTML style empty element (`<br/>` to `<br>`).
[src:webview-native/html] Those are the main changes necessary to translate a document from XHTML 1.0 to HTML 4.01.
[src:webview-native/html] To translate from HTML to XHTML would also require the addition of any omitted opening or closing tags.
[src:webview-native/html] Whether coding in HTML or XHTML it may just be best to always include the optional tags within an HTML document rather than remembering which tags can be omitted.
[src:webview-native/html] A well-formed XHTML document adheres to all the syntax requirements of XML.
[src:webview-native/html] A valid document adheres to the content specification for XHTML, which describes the document structure.
[src:webview-native/html] The W3C recommends several conventions to ensure an easy migration between HTML and XHTML.
[src:webview-native/html] By carefully following the W3C's compatibility guidelines, a user agent should be able to interpret the document equally as HTML or XHTML.
[src:webview-native/html] For documents that are XHTML 1.0 and have been made compatible in this way, the W3C permits them to be served either as HTML (with a `text/html` MIME type), or as XHTML (with an `application/xhtml+xml` or `application/xml` MIME type).
[src:webview-native/html] When delivered as XHTML, browsers should use an XML parser, which adheres strictly to the XML specifications for parsing the document's contents.
[src:webview-native/html] HTML 4 defined three different versions of the language: Strict, Transitional (once called Loose), and Frameset.
[src:webview-native/html] The Strict version is intended for new documents and is considered best practice, while the Transitional and Frameset versions were developed to make it easier to transition documents that conformed to older HTML specifications or did not conform to any specification to a version of HTML 4.
[src:webview-native/html] The Transitional and Frameset versions allow for presentational markup, which is omitted in the Strict version.
[src:webview-native/html] Instead, cascading style sheets are encouraged to improve the presentation of HTML documents.
[src:webview-native/html] Because XHTML 1 only defines an XML syntax for the language defined by HTML 4, the same differences apply to XHTML 1 as well.
[src:webview-native/html] The Frameset version includes everything in the Transitional version, as well as the `frameset` element (used instead of `body`) and the `frame` element.
[src:webview-native/html] In addition to the above transitional differences, the frameset specifications (whether XHTML 1.0 or HTML 4.01) specify a different content model, with `frameset` replacing `body`, that contains either `frame` elements, or optionally `noframes` with a `body`.
[src:webview-native/html] As this list demonstrates, the loose versions of the specification are maintained for legacy support.
[src:webview-native/html] However, contrary to popular misconceptions, the move to XHTML does not imply a removal of this legacy support.
[src:webview-native/html] Rather the X in XML stands for extensible and the W3C is modularizing the entire specification and opens it up to independent extensions.
[src:webview-native/html] The primary achievement in the move from XHTML 1.0 to XHTML 1.1 is the modularization of the entire specification.
[src:webview-native/html] The strict version of HTML is deployed in XHTML 1.1 through a set of modular extensions to the base XHTML 1.1 specification.
[src:webview-native/html] Likewise, someone looking for the loose (transitional) or frameset specifications will find similar extended XHTML 1.1 support (much of it is contained in the legacy or frame modules).
[src:webview-native/html] Modularization also allows for separate features to develop on their own timetable.
[src:webview-native/html] So for example, XHTML 1.1 will allow quicker migration to emerging XML standards such as MathML (a presentational and semantic math language based on XML) and XForms—a new highly advanced web-form technology to replace the existing HTML forms.
[src:webview-native/html] In summary, the HTML 4 specification primarily reined in all the various HTML implementations into a single clearly written specification based on SGML.
[src:webview-native/html] XHTML 1.0, ported this specification, as is, to the new XML-defined specification.
[src:webview-native/html] Next, XHTML 1.1 takes advantage of the extensible nature of XML and modularizes the whole specification.
[src:webview-native/html] XHTML 2.0 was intended to be the first step in adding new features to the specification in a standards-body-based approach.
[src:webview-native/html] The HTML Living Standard, which is developed by WHATWG, is the official version, while W3C HTML5 is no longer separate from WHATWG.
[src:webview-native/html] WYSIWYG editors (*what you see is what you get*), are HTML editors in which the user lays out everything as it is to appear in the HTML document using a graphical user interface (GUI), such as Microsoft FrontPage, often similar to word processors.
[src:webview-native/html] The editor renders the document rather than showing the code, so authors do not require extensive knowledge of HTML.
[src:webview-native/html] The WYSIWYG editing model has been criticized, primarily because of the low quality of the generated code; there are various developers advocating a change to the WYSIWYM model (*what you see is what you mean*).
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] A **web application** (or **web app**) is application software that is created with web technologies and runs via a web browser.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Web applications emerged during the late 1990s and allowed for the server to dynamically build a response to the request, in contrast to static web pages.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Web applications are commonly distributed via a web server.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] There are several different tier systems that web applications use to communicate between the web browsers, the client interface, and server data.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Each system has its own uses as they function in different ways.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] However, there are many security risks that developers must be aware of during development; proper measures to protect user data are vital.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Web applications are often constructed with the use of a web application framework.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Single-page applications (SPAs) and progressive web apps (PWAs) are two architectural approaches to creating web applications that provide a user experience similar to native apps, including features such as smooth navigation, offline support, and faster interactions.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Modern browsers such as Chrome offer sandboxing for every browser tab which improves security and restricts access to local resources.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] No software installation is required as the app runs within the browser which reduces the need for managing software installations.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] With the use of remote cloud services, customers do not need to manage servers as that can be left to the developer and the cloud service and can use the software with a relatively low power, low-resource PC such as a thin client.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] The source code of the application can stay the same across operating systems and devices of users with the use of responsive web design, since it only needs to be compatible with web browsers which adhere to web standards, making the code highly portable and saving on development time.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Numerous JavaScript frameworks and CSS frameworks facilitate development.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] The concept of a "web application" was first introduced in the Java language in the Servlet Specification version 2.2, which was released in 1999.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] At that time, both JavaScript and XML had already been developed, but the XMLHttpRequest object had only been recently introduced on Internet Explorer 5 as an ActiveX object.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Beginning around the early 2000s, applications such as "Myspace (2003), Gmail (2004), Digg (2004), [and] Google Maps (2005)," started to make their client sides more and more interactive.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] A web page script is able to contact the server for storing/retrieving data without downloading an entire web page.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] The practice became known as Ajax in 2005.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Eventually this was replaced by web APIs using JSON, accessed via JavaScript asynchronously on the client side.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] In earlier computing models like client-server, the processing load for the application was shared between code on the server and code installed on each client locally.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] In other words, an application had its own pre-compiled client program which served as its user interface and had to be separately installed on each user's personal computer.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] An upgrade to the server-side code of the application would typically also require an upgrade to the client-side code installed on each user workstation, adding to the support cost and decreasing productivity.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Additionally, both the client and server components of the application were bound tightly to a particular computer architecture and operating system, which made porting them to other systems prohibitively expensive for all but the largest applications.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Later, in 1995, Netscape introduced the client-side scripting language called JavaScript, which allowed programmers to add dynamic elements to the user interface that ran on the client side.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Essentially, instead of sending data to the server in order to generate an entire web page, the embedded scripts of the downloaded page can perform various tasks such as input validation or showing/hiding parts of the page.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Traditional PC applications are typically single-tiered, residing solely on the client machine.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] In contrast, web applications inherently facilitate a multi-tiered architecture.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Though many variations are possible, the most common structure is the three-tiered application.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] In its most common form, the three tiers are called *presentation*, *application* and *storage*.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] The first tier, presentation, refers to a web browser itself.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] The second tier refers to any engine using dynamic web content technology (such as ASP, CGI, ColdFusion, Dart, JSP/Java, Node.js, PHP, Python or Ruby on Rails).
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] The third tier refers to a database that stores data and determines the structure of a user interface.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Essentially, when using the three-tiered system, the web browser sends requests to the engine, which then services them by making queries and updates against the database and generates a user interface.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] The 3-tier solution may fall short when dealing with more complex applications, and may need to be replaced with the n-tiered approach; the greatest benefit of which is how business logic (which resides on the application tier) is broken down into a more fine-grained model.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Another benefit would be to add an integration tier, which separates the data tier and provides an easy-to-use interface to access the data.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] For example, the client data would be accessed by calling a "list_clients()" function instead of making an SQL query directly against the client table on the database.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] This allows the underlying database to be replaced without making any change to the other tiers.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] There are some who view a web application as a two-tier architecture.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] This can be a "smart" client that performs all the work and queries a "dumb" server, or a "dumb" client that relies on a "smart" server.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] The client would handle the presentation tier, the server would have the database (storage tier), and the business logic (application tier) would be on one of them or on both.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] While this increases the scalability of the applications and separates the display and the database, it still does not allow for true specialization of layers, so most applications will outgrow this model.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Security breaches on these kinds of applications are a major concern because it can involve both enterprise information and private customer data.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Protecting these assets is an important part of any web application, and there are some key operational areas that must be included in the development process.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] This includes processes for authentication, authorization, asset handling, input, and logging and auditing.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Building security into the applications from the beginning is sometimes more effective and less disruptive in the long run.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] Writing web applications is simplified with the use of web application frameworks.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] These frameworks facilitate rapid application development by allowing a development team to focus on the parts of their application which are unique to their goals without having to resolve common development issues such as user management.
[src:webview-native/hybrid-app] In addition, there is potential for the development of applications on Internet operating systems, although currently there are not many viable platforms that fit this model.
[src:webview-native/webkit] WebKit started as a fork of the KHTML and KJS libraries from KDE, and has since been further developed by KDE contributors, Apple, Google, Nokia, Bitstream, BlackBerry, Sony, Igalia, and others.
[src:webview-native/webkit] WebKit supports macOS, Windows, Linux, and various other Unix-like operating systems.
[src:webview-native/webkit] On April 3, 2013, Google announced that it had forked WebCore, a component of WebKit, to be used in future versions of Google Chrome under the name Blink.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Since version 15 in May 2013, Opera web browser has dropped its own Presto layout engine in favor of WebKit as implemented by Google in the Chromium project.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Its JavaScript engine, JavaScriptCore, also powers the Bun server-side JS runtime, as opposed to V8 used by Node.js, Deno, and Blink.
[src:webview-native/webkit] WebKit's C++ application programming interface (API) provides a set of classes to display Web content in windows, and implements browser features such as following links when clicked by the user, managing a back-forward list, and managing a history of pages recently visited.
[src:webview-native/webkit] WebKit is open source and available under the BSD 2-Clause license with the exception of the WebCore and JavaScriptCore components, which are available under the GNU Lesser General Public License.
[src:webview-native/webkit] As of March 7, 2013, WebKit is a trademark of Apple, registered with the United States Patent and Trademark Office.
[src:webview-native/webkit] The code that would become WebKit began in 1998 as the *KDE HTML* (KHTML) layout engine and *KDE JavaScript* (KJS) engine.
[src:webview-native/webkit] The WebKit project was started within Apple by Lisa Melton on June 25, 2001, as a fork of KHTML and KJS.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Melton explained in an e-mail to KDE developers that KHTML and KJS allowed easier development than other available technologies by virtue of being small (fewer than 140,000 lines of code), cleanly designed, and standards-compliant.
[src:webview-native/webkit] KHTML and KJS were ported to macOS with the help of an adapter library and renamed to WebCore and JavaScriptCore.
[src:webview-native/webkit] JavaScriptCore was announced in an e-mail to a KDE mailing list in June 2002, alongside the first release of Apple's changes.
[src:webview-native/webkit] The exchange of code between WebCore and KHTML became increasingly difficult as the code bases diverged, because both projects used different coding approaches and had different approaches to code sharing.
[src:webview-native/webkit] At one point KHTML developers said they were unlikely to accept Apple's changes and claimed the relationship between the two groups was a "bitter failure".
[src:webview-native/webkit] They claimed Apple submitted their changes in large patches containing multiple changes with inadequate documentation, often in relation to future additions to the codebase.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Thus, these patches were difficult for the KDE developers to integrate back into KHTML.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Also, Apple had demanded that developers sign non-disclosure agreements before looking at Apple's source code, and even then, they were unable to access Apple's bug database.
[src:webview-native/webkit] During the publicized "divorce" period, KDE developer Kurt Pfeifle (*pipitas*) posted an article claiming KHTML developers had managed to backport many (but not all) Safari improvements from WebCore to KHTML, and they always appreciated the improvements coming from Apple and still do so.
[src:webview-native/webkit] The article also noted that Apple had begun contacting KHTML developers to discuss improving the relationship and future cooperation.
[src:webview-native/webkit] In fact, the KDE project was able to incorporate some of these changes to improve KHTML's rendering speed and add features, including compliance with the Acid2 rendering test.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Following the appearance of a story of the fork in the news, Apple released the source code of the WebKit fork in a public revision-control repository.
[src:webview-native/webkit] The WebKit team also reversed many Apple-specific changes in the original WebKit codebase and implemented platform-specific abstraction layers, making it significantly easier to commit the core rendering code to other platforms.
[src:webview-native/webkit] In July 2007, *Ars Technica* reported that the KDE team would move from KHTML to WebKit.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Instead, after several years of integration, KDE Development Platform version 4.5.0 was released in August 2010 with support for both WebKit and KHTML, and development of KHTML continued until 2016 before it was officially discontinued in 2023.
[src:webview-native/webkit] On June 7, 2005, Safari developer Dave Hyatt announced on his weblog that Apple was open-sourcing WebKit (formerly, only WebCore and JavaScriptCore were open source) and opening up access to WebKit's revision control tree and the issue tracker.
[src:webview-native/webkit] In mid-December 2005, support for Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) was merged into the standard build.
[src:webview-native/webkit] WebKit's JavaScriptCore and WebCore components are available under the GNU Lesser General Public License, while the rest of WebKit is available under the BSD 2-Clause license.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Beginning in early 2007, the development team began to implement Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) extensions, including animation, transitions and both 2D and 3D transforms; such extensions were released as working drafts to the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) in 2009 for standardization.
[src:webview-native/webkit] In November 2007, the project announced that it had added support for media features of the HTML5 draft specification, allowing embedded video to be natively rendered and script-controlled in WebKit.
[src:webview-native/webkit] On June 2, 2008, the WebKit project announced that they had rewritten JavaScriptCore as "SquirrelFish", a bytecode interpreter.
[src:webview-native/webkit] The project evolved into SquirrelFish Extreme (abbreviated SFX), announced on September 18, 2008, which compiles JavaScript into native machine code, eliminating the need for a bytecode interpreter and thus speeding up JavaScript execution.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Initially, the only supported processor architecture for SFX was the x86, but at the end of January 2009, SFX was enabled for macOS on x86-64 as it passes all tests on that platform.
[src:webview-native/webkit] On April 8, 2010, a project named WebKit2 was announced to redesign WebKit.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Its goal was to abstract the components that provide page layout and rendering cleanly from their surrounding interface or application shell, creating a situation where "web content (JavaScript, HTML, layout, etc) lives in a separate process from the application UI".
[src:webview-native/webkit] This abstraction was intended to make reuse in WebKit2 simpler than in WebKit.
[src:webview-native/webkit] WebKit2 had "an incompatible API change from the original WebKit", which motivated its name change.
[src:webview-native/webkit] The WebKit2 targets were set to Linux, macOS, Windows, GTK, and MeeGo-Harmattan.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Safari for macOS switched to the new API with version 5.1.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Safari for iOS switched to WebKit2 with iOS 8.
[src:webview-native/webkit] The original WebKit API has been renamed WebKitLegacy API.
[src:webview-native/webkit] WebKit2 API has been renamed just plain WebKit API.
[src:webview-native/webkit] WebKit is used as the rendering engine within Safari and was used by Google's Chrome web browser on Windows, macOS, and Android (before version 4.4 KitKat).
[src:webview-native/webkit] Chrome used only WebCore, and included its own JavaScript engine named V8 and a multiprocess system.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Chrome for iOS continues to use WebKit because Apple requires that web browsers on that platform must do so.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Other applications on macOS and iOS make use of WebKit, such as Apple's e-mail client Mail, App Store, and the 2008 version of Microsoft's Entourage personal information manager, both of which make use of WebKit to render HTML content.
[src:webview-native/webkit] New web browsers have been built around WebKit such as the S60 browser on Symbian mobile phones, BlackBerry Browser (ver 6.0+), Midori, Chrome browser, the Android Web browsers before version 4.4 KitKat, and the browser used in PlayStation 3 system software from version 4.10.
[src:webview-native/webkit] KDE's Rekonq web browser and Plasma Workspaces also use it as the native web rendering engine.
[src:webview-native/webkit] WebKit has been adopted as the rendering engine in OmniWeb, iCab, Web (formerly named Epiphany), and Sleipnir, replacing their original rendering engines.
[src:webview-native/webkit] GNOME's Web supported both Gecko and WebKit for some time.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Still, the team decided that Gecko's release cycle and future development plans would make it too cumbersome to continue supporting it. webOS uses WebKit as the basis of its application runtime.
[src:webview-native/webkit] WebKit is used to render HTML and run JavaScript in the Adobe Integrated Runtime application platform.
[src:webview-native/webkit] In Adobe Creative Suite CS5, WebKit is used to render some parts of the user interface.
[src:webview-native/webkit] By the first half of 2010, an analyst estimated that 350 million mobile handsets had shipped with a WebKit-based browser.
[src:webview-native/webkit] By mid-April 2015, WebKit browser market share was 50.3%.
[src:webview-native/webkit] The week after Hyatt announced WebKit's open sourcing, Nokia announced that it had ported WebKit to Symbian and was developing a WebKit-based browser for mobile phones running S60.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Named Web Browser for S60, it was used on Nokia, Samsung, LG, and other Symbian S60 mobile phones.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Apple has also ported WebKit to iOS for the iPhone, iPod Touch, and iPad, where it is used to render content in the device's web browser and e-mail software.
[src:webview-native/webkit] The Android mobile phone platform used WebKit (and later versions its Blink fork) as the basis of its web browser and the Palm Pre, announced January 2009, has an interface based on WebKit.
[src:webview-native/webkit] The Amazon Kindle 3 includes an experimental WebKit based browser.
[src:webview-native/webkit] In June 2007, Apple announced that WebKit had been ported to Microsoft Windows as part of Safari.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Although the company silently discontinued Safari for Windows, WebKit's ports to Microsoft's operating system are still actively maintained.
[src:webview-native/webkit] The Windows port uses Apple's proprietary libraries to function and is used for iCloud and iTunes for Windows, whereas the "WinCairo" port is a fully open-source and redistributable port.
[src:webview-native/webkit] WebKit has also been ported to several toolkits that support multiple platforms, such as the GTK toolkit for Linux, under the name *WebKitGTK* which is used by Eolie, GNOME Web, Adobe Integrated Runtime, Enlightenment Foundation Libraries (EFL), and the Clutter toolkit.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Qt Software included a WebKit port in the Qt 4.4 release as a module called QtWebKit (since superseded by Qt WebEngine, which uses Blink instead).
[src:webview-native/webkit] The Iris Browser on Qt also used WebKit.
[src:webview-native/webkit] The Enlightenment Foundation Libraries (EFL) port – EWebKit – was developed (by Samsung and ProFusion) focusing the embedded and mobile systems, for use as stand alone browser, widgets-gadgets, rich text viewer and composer.
[src:webview-native/webkit] The Clutter port is developed by Collabora and sponsored by Robert Bosch GmbH.
[src:webview-native/webkit] There was also a project synchronized with WebKit (sponsored by Pleyo) called *Origyn Web Browser*, which provided a meta-port to an abstract platform to make porting to embedded or lightweight systems quicker and easier.
[src:webview-native/webkit] This port is used for embedded devices such as set-top boxes and PMP and it has been ported into AmigaOS, AROS, and MorphOS.
[src:webview-native/webkit] MorphOS version 1.7 is the first version of Origyn Web Browser (OWB) supporting HTML5 media tags.
[src:webview-native/webkit] On April 3, 2013, Google announced that it would produce a fork of WebKit's WebCore component, to be named Blink.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Chrome's developers decided to fork WebCore to allow greater freedom in implementing its features in the browser without causing conflicts upstream, and to simplify its codebase by removing code for WebCore components unused by Chrome.
[src:webview-native/webkit] In relation to Opera Software's announcement earlier in the year that it would switch to WebKit by means of the Chromium codebase, it was confirmed that the Opera web browser would also switch to Blink.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Following the announcement, WebKit developers began discussions on removing Chrome-specific code from the engine to streamline its codebase.
[src:webview-native/webkit] WebKit no longer has any Chrome specific code (e.g., buildsystem, V8 JavaScript engine hooks, platform code, etc.).
[src:webview-native/webkit] WebCore is a layout, rendering, and Document Object Model (DOM) library for HTML and Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG), developed by the WebKit project.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Its full source code is licensed under the GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL).
[src:webview-native/webkit] WebKit passes the Acid2 and Acid3 tests, with pixel-perfect rendering and no timing or smoothness issues on reference hardware.
[src:webview-native/webkit] JavaScriptCore is a framework that provides a JavaScript engine for WebKit implementations, and provides this type of scripting in other contexts within macOS.
[src:webview-native/webkit] JavaScriptCore is originally derived from KDE's JavaScript library KJS (which is part of the KDE project) and the PCRE regular expression library.
[src:webview-native/webkit] Since forking from KJS and PCRE, JavaScriptCore has added many new features and greatly improved performance.
[src:webview-native/webkit] On June 2, 2008, the WebKit project announced they rewrote JavaScriptCore as "SquirrelFish", a register-based bytecode interpreter replacing the original AST-walking interpreter.
[src:webview-native/webkit] The project later evolved into SquirrelFish Extreme (abbreviated SFX, marketed as Nitro), announced on September 18, 2008, further speeding up JavaScript execution by introducing Just-in-time compilation.
[src:webview-native/webkit] An optimizing just-in-time (JIT) compiler named *FTL* was announced on May 13, 2014.
[src:webview-native/webkit] It uses LLVM to generate optimized machine code.
[src:webview-native/webkit] "FTL" stands for "Fourth-Tier-LLVM", and unofficially for faster-than-light, alluding to its speed.
[src:webview-native/webkit] As of February 15, 2016, the backend of FTL JIT is replaced by "Bare Bones Backend" (or B3 for short).
[src:webview-native/webview] A **WebView** is a web browser that is embedded within an app.
[src:webview-native/webview] Thus, a WebView is a large-scale software component that enables the use of web content within apps.
[src:webview-native/webview] In some cases, the entire functionality of the app is implemented this way.
[src:webview-native/webview] Other examples are Microsoft's legacy WebView, based on its deprecated EdgeHTML and MSHTML engines, and the WebView component in JavaFX.
